Value of banana: 2
```

If you define an `operator=` function in a parent class, you should be able to use it to copy instances of child classes. However, there are a few possible reasons why you might be experiencing issues:

1. The `operator=` function might not be defined correctly in the parent class. Make sure that it is properly defined to handle the copying of both the parent class's members and any additional members that might be added by the child class. Also, make sure that it returns a reference to the object being assigned to (`*this`), so that chained assignments are possible.

2. The `operator=` function in the child class might not be defined correctly. If the child defines its own `operator=`, it can hide the parent class's `operator=` unless it specifically calls it. The child class's `operator=` should call the parent class's `operator=` in order to properly copy the parent's members.

3. The child class might have a non-copyable member. If the class has a member object or base class that is not copyable (e.g. if it has a deleted copy constructor), the assignment operator generated by the compiler may be deleted, preventing you from using the `operator=` to copy the child class instance.

Here is an example illustrating how to define and use an `operator=` in a parent class to copy instances of child classes:

```c++
#include <iostream>

class Parent {
protected:
    int parentValue;

public:
    Parent(int value) : parentValue(value) {}

    Parent& operator=(const Parent& other) {
        if (this != &other) {
            parentValue = other.parentValue;
        }
        return *this;
    }
};

class Child : public Parent {
private:
    int childValue;

public:
    Child(int parent, int child) : Parent(parent), childValue(child) {}

    Child& operator=(const Child& other) {
        if (this != &other) {
            Parent::operator=(other);
            childValue = other.childValue;
        }
        return *this;
    }

    void printValues() {
        std::cout << "Parent value: " << parentValue << std::endl;
        std::cout << "Child value: " << childValue << std::endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Child child1(10, 20);
    Child child2(30, 40);
    child1.printValues(); // Output: Parent value: 10 Child value: 20
    child2.printValues(); // Output: Parent value: 30 Child value: 40

    child1 = child2;
    child1.printValues(); // Output: Parent value: 30 Child value: 40

    return 0;
}
```

